nerve","Flexor hallucis longus","Flexor digitorum longus"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe tarsal tunnel contains several structures that pass from the leg into the foot, arranged from anterior to posterior. The \u003Cstrong\u003Etibialis posterior\u003C/strong\u003E tendon is the most anterior structure within the tarsal tunnel. The \u003Cstrong\u003Eflexor digitorum longus\u003C/strong\u003E tendon lies just posterior to it, followed by the \u003Cstrong\u003Etibial artery and veins\u003C/strong\u003E, then the \u003Cstrong\u003Etibial nerve\u003C/strong\u003E, and finally the \u003Cstrong\u003Eflexor hallucis longus\u003C/strong\u003E tendon, which is the most posterior. This anatomical arrangement is clinically relevant for diagnosing and managing tarsal tunnel syndrome and for surgical interventions in the region.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The tibialis posterior tendon is the most anterior structure within the tarsal tunnel.","The tarsal tunnel contains, from anterior to posterior: tibialis posterior tendon, flexor digitorum longus tendon, posterior tibial artery and veins, tibial nerve, and flexor hallucis longus tendon."],"references":["Patton, K. T., \u0026 Thibodeau, G. A. (2018). Anthony\u0027s Textbook of Anatomy \u0026 Physiology-E-Book: Anthony\u0027s Textbook of Anatomy \u0026 Physiology-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Smith, R., \u0026 Wordsworth, P. (2016). Oxford textbook of clinical and biochemical disorders of the skeleton. Oxford University Press","Kiel J, Kaiser K. Tarsal Tunnel Syndrome. [Updated 2024 Feb 9]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2025 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK513273/","Sud, A., \u0026 Ranjan, R. (2021). Textbook of Orthopaedics, 2e-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Dandy, D. J., \u0026 Edwards, D. J. (2009). Essential Orthopaedics and Trauma E-Book. Elsevier Health Scie